markdown: CHART 19.- PER CAPITA CONSUMPTION OF GRAIN PRODUCTS AND MAJOR PRODUCTS OF MILK (EXCLUDING BUTTER), FROM 1879* (Calories per day) <::transcription of the content : chart::> This line chart displays the per capita consumption of grain products and major products of milk (excluding butter) in calories per day from 1875 to 1955. The x-axis represents years from 1875 to 1955. The y-axis (left and right) represents calories per day, ranging from 0 to 1,800. Two main data series are shown: 1. **Grain products**: This line starts at approximately 1,700 calories per day in 1879 and shows a general downward trend, reaching around 750 calories per day by 1955. There are some fluctuations, notably a dip around 1918 and another around 1945. 2. **Major milk products**: This line starts at approximately 300 calories per day in 1879 and shows a general upward trend, reaching around 400 calories per day by 1955. An arrow points from this line to the label "Fluid milk", indicating it's a component. Below the "Major milk products" line, three other lines represent specific milk products, all showing an increasing trend over the period, particularly from the 1930s onwards: 1. **Ice cream**: This line starts near 0 and increases to approximately 50 calories per day by 1955. 2. **Evap. + cond. milk**: This line starts near 0 and increases to approximately 75 calories per day by 1955. 3. **Cheese**: This line starts near 0 and increases to approximately 25 calories per day by 1955. <:: *Data from Part E, Tables VI-A, VIII, IX. Source: https://www.industrydocuments.ucsf.edu/docs/tkyg0227
